    "body": "## Summary\r\nThis PR adds end-to-end Windows support for TileLang across build, packaging, runtime loading, and developer setup.\r\nAlong the way, it also fixes several cross-platform issues uncovered during the Windows bring-up, especially around CUDA toolkit discovery, MSVC compatibility, runtime DLL loading, logging, and layout/reducer handling.\r\n## Main changes\r\n- add native Windows support in the build and packaging flow\r\n- support pip-installed CUDA toolkits on Windows, including NVCC/NVRTC-based workflows\r\n- add Windows-specific MSVC environment bootstrap helpers\r\n- add a Windows helper script for setting up a local development environment\r\n- improve runtime DLL discovery and PATH setup on Windows\r\n- update installation docs and packaging metadata for Windows\r\n## Bug fixes\r\n- avoid enabling CUDA by default when no CUDA toolkit is available\r\n- fix NVRTC import-library handling on Windows\r\n- fix several MSVC build issues, including:\r\n  - Python debug import library auto-linking\r\n  - `TVM_DLL` import/export behavior\r\n  - designated initializer compilation\r\n  - large CUDA intrinsic dispatch paths in codegen\r\n- normalize Windows file paths for `TVM_LOG_DEBUG`\r\n- make reducer/layout handling more robust when reducer annotations are absent or layout information is still in hint form\r\n- improve runtime library lookup behavior for local/dev builds on Windows\r\n## TODO / Follow-ups\r\n- [x] clean up and optimize the dynamic-loading (`dynload`) polyfill\r\n- [x] investigate the ROCm regression; currently suspected to be a compatibility break introduced by a recent nightly\r\n- [x] optimize and reuse CUDA toolkit lookup results to avoid redundant probing\r\n- [x] fix concurrency/thread-safety issues in the autotuner on Windows\r\n## Known issues\r\n- MSVC is significantly slower than GCC/Clang at compiling CUTE headers; we may need to introduce on-demand / lazy includes to keep build times reasonable on Windows.\r\n- `cutlass-dsl` does not officially support Windows, so any code paths depending on it are currently unavailable in the Windows build.\r\n- CUDA 13 requires 128-byte alignment in some places, but MSVC only supports up to 64-byte alignment for `__declspec(align(...))` if is not newer than `17.10`. As a workaround, we use a torch-style fallback that degrades to the largest alignment MSVC accepts; this matches PyTorch's behavior but means the strict CUDA 13 alignment guarantee is not preserved on MSVC.\r\n\r\n<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->\r\n## Summary by CodeRabbit\r\n## Release Notes\r\n* **New Features**\r\n  * Full Windows platform support with MSVC compiler integration and native CUDA runtime compatibility\r\n  * Windows-specific NVRTC and CUDA toolkit installation via package manager\r\n* **Improvements**\r\n  * Enhanced Windows build infrastructure and CMake configuration\r\n  * Improved Windows installation documentation with Visual Studio Developer Command Prompt guidance\r\n  * Cross-platform dynamic library loading support\r\n  * Better debug logging configuration capabilities\r\n* **Bug Fixes**\r\n  * Fixed CUDA stub compatibility on Windows\r\n  * Corrected platform-specific library path handling\r\n<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->",
